This paper discusses distributional semantics, which is a subfield of computational linguistics (cs.CL) that uses statistical methods to analyze the distribution of words in large corpora. The paper also mentions the use of machine learning algorithms (cs.LG) to induce word representations. Additionally, the paper discusses the empirical nature of distributional semantics, which is related to artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also briefly mentions the use of clustering algorithms (cs.CC) to group similar words together based on their distributional properties. Finally, the paper discusses the potential applications of distributional semantics in cryptography (cs.CR).
